<a name="eztoc353253_1" id="eztoc353253_1"></a><h2><b>10th Meeting of the Advisory Committee on Science and Technology for ACP Agricultural &amp; Rural Development Safeguarding the ACP Food System through Science, Technology and Innovation</b></h2><a name="eztoc353253_1_1" id="eztoc353253_1_1"></a><h3><b>--</b></h3><a name="eztoc353253_1_2" id="eztoc353253_1_2"></a><h3><b>Final Draft Programme</b></h3><a name="eztoc353253_1_3" id="eztoc353253_1_3"></a><h3><b>--</b></h3><a name="eztoc353253_1_4" id="eztoc353253_1_4"></a><h3><b>Venue: Garraway Hotel, Commonwealth of Dominica</b></h3><a name="eztoc353253_1_5" id="eztoc353253_1_5"></a><h3><b>Dates: October 09-13, 2011 </b></h3><a name="eztoc353253_1_5_1" id="eztoc353253_1_5_1"></a><h4><b>--</b></h4><a name="eztoc353253_1_5_2" id="eztoc353253_1_5_2"></a><h4><b>Background</b></h4><p>The 2010 GCARD confirmed that the global architecture for agricultural research and development (R&amp;D) must be restructured and that national innovation systems should be strengthened to deal with the complex inter-related issues impacting on the agri-food system. While S&amp;T advances are increasing at lightning speed and scientific domains are becoming more interconnected, challenges persist for feeding the growing population while responding to climate change, ongoing volatility in food and energy markets, intensifying agricultural production sustainably and adding value along the production to consumption chain without further depleting the natural resource base; land, water and biodiversity. Since 2003, CTA has convened the annual meeting of the Advisory Committee on S&amp;T for ACP Agricultural and Rural Development (AC), a multi-stakeholder ACP/EU platform which deliberates on S&amp;T issues of vital importance to ACP agriculture. The recommendations inform the work of national, regional and international organizations. </p><p>In 2010, the AC identified improving the ACP postharvest knowledge system as a priority issue to be addressed. This was considered of strategic importance because of high postharvest losses due to poor pre-production and postharvest handling and limited availability of suitable processing, marketing and transport infrastructure as well as, limited policy support, research and development and inadequate information, knowledge and skills to facilitate strategic decision-making and support intervention for strengthening the postharvest knowledge system. In 2011, the UK Foresight Group released its report “the Future of Food and Farming: Challenges and Choices for Global Sustainability”. Five challenges were identified: (a) balancing future demand and supply sustainably to ensure affordability; (b) stability in food supplies in face of volatility in the food system; (c) ending hunger; (d) managing the contribution of the food system to climate change and; (e) maintaining biodiversity and ecosystem services while feeding the world. The team further noted that all the challenges are interconnected and that no single policy or approach will be successful. Among the key priorities proposed for addressing the challenges were: (a) spreading best practice; (b) investing in new knowledge; (c) reducing food waste and; (d) improving the evidence base on which decisions are made. </p><p>In 2011, CTA approved its strategic plan 2011-2015 which features the attainment of three strategic goals namely; strengthening ACP agricultural and rural development policy processes and strategies, enhancing priority agricultural value chains and enhancing ACP capacities in information, communication and knowledge management for ARD. The 10th AC meeting will focus on identifying options and strategies that scientists and policymakers need to pursue and decisions that need to be taken now and in the years ahead to ensure the sustainability of the ACP food systems. Emphasis will be on reducing food waste and learning from best practice to provide the evidence to support policy and decision-making. This is in-line with the CTA SP and will contribute to achieving impact on; food security, prosperity and sound natural resources management. The AC will also reflect on the outcomes of the evaluation of the CTA SP 2007-2010 as it relates to the AC and discuss how collective activities of AC members can contribute to the attainment of the goals.</p><p>The theme for the 10th AC meeting in the Commonwealth of Dominica is “<b>Safeguarding the ACP Food System through Science, Technology and Innovation”</b>. It will be held during the Caribbean Week of Agriculture, in Dominica and the outputs will be presented during the Alliance Meeting to contribute to decisive actions that policymakers can take for safeguarding the ACP food system. This is appropriate as AC members continue their efforts to advocate for policy and institutional change and adequate financial resources, for undertaking innovative research and teaching to generate and apply new and existing knowledge in support of agricultural innovation and enhanced performance for socio-economic development. </p><a name="eztoc353253_1_5_3" id="eztoc353253_1_5_3"></a><h4><b>Objectives</b></h4><p>The main objectives of the 10th AC meeting are as follows: </p>
<ol>

<li> To achieve shared understanding and consensus on the S&amp;T priorities for policy intervention and for building policy coherence for reducing food waste and safeguarding the ACP agri-food system. </li>

<li>To take stock of existing knowledge and initiatives from the ACP, EU and internationally to identify best practices and propose policies and strategies for improving the evidence base for strengthening the ACP postharvest knowledge system.</li>

<li>To identify the strategic priorities of the CTA S&amp;T programme and determine the future Role and Modus Operandi of the Advisory Committee for influencing key ACP ARD policy processes to increase agricultural productivity for food security and enhance innovation in priority agricultural value chains.</li>

</ol>
<a name="eztoc353253_1_5_4" id="eztoc353253_1_5_4"></a><h4><b>Expected Outputs</b></h4><p><b> </b>In-depth deliberations held on reducing food waste in the ACP agri-food system; </p><p>Best practices identified and evaluated and policy options, interventions and strategies prioritized for strengthening ACP postharvest knowledge system;</p><p>Commitment of leaders of the S&amp;T community to work closely with policy and decision makers, CTA and other ACP/EU actors engaged in ongoing ACP ARD policy processes to ensure science and policy coherence and availability of evidence for making decisions that safeguard the future of the ACP agri-food system and contribute to food security goals and innovations in priority agricultural value chains;</p><p>Communiqué and report of meeting which includes a range of well defined and clearly articulated policy options and strategies for strengthening the ACP postharvest knowledge system published, promoted and widely disseminated through the ACP region and internationally. </p><p>Strategy formulated and endorsed on the future S&amp;T priorities for the CTA S&amp;T programme and the role and modus operandi of the Advisory Committee to include impact pathways for monitoring and evaluating the influence of the programme and the AC on ACP ST&amp;I and ARD policy processes.</p><a name="eztoc353253_1_5_5" id="eztoc353253_1_5_5"></a><h4><b>Outcome</b></h4><p>S&amp;T community’s contribution to the sustainability and improved performance of the ACP agri-food system, for assuring food security, prosperity and sound natural resource management recognized, valued as relevant and effective.</p><a name="eztoc353253_1_5_6" id="eztoc353253_1_5_6"></a><h4><b>PROGRAMME</b></h4><p><b> </b></p><p><b>Day 1 - October 09</b></p><p>8:30 Depart Hotel for Arawak Cultural Centre</p><p>9:30 – 12:30 Joint Opening Ceremony: Climate Change and S&amp;T Workshops</p><p>9:30 – 9:35 Chairperson – Professor Dyer Narinesingh, Dean Faculty of Science and Agriculture, UWI, St. Augustine Campus, Trinidad &amp; Tobago</p><p>9:35 – 9:45 Opening Prayer and Invocation; National Anthem of Dominica</p><p>9:45 – 10:00 Welcome Remarks – Hon. Dr. Kenneth Darroux, Minister of Environment, Natural Resources, Physical Planning &amp; Fisheries, Commonwealth of Dominica </p><p>10:00 – 10:15 Remarks for CWA 2011 - Hon Matthew Walter, Minister of Agriculture and Forestry, Commonwealth of Dominica (tbc)</p><p>10:15 – 10:25 Remarks - Mr. Michael Hailu, Director, CTA, The Netherlands</p><p>10:25 - 10:45 Keynote Address – Global Climate Change and Agricultural Water Management in the Caribbean - Professor Chandra Madramootoo, Dean of the Faculty of Agricultural and Environmental Sciences, McGill University, Canada</p><p>10:45 – 11:05 Keynote Address - Investing in Science and Innovation: The Chicken or the Egg? – Prof. Bongani Ndimba, FP7 National Contact Point for the Knowledge-based Bio-Economy, Agricultural Research Council (ARC), South Africa </p><p>11:05 – 11:35 Feature Address – Hon Roosevelt Skerrette – Prime Minister of the Commonwealth of Dominica* (tbc)</p><p>11:35 – 11:45 Vote of Thanks – Dr. H. Arlington D. Chesney, Executive Director, Caribbean Agricultural Research and Development Institute (CARDI), Trinidad and Tobago</p><p>11:45 – 12:30 Refreshment (including Group Photo shoot)</p><p>12:30 Departure for Hotel</p><p>13:00 – 14:00 Lunch (Garraway Hotel)</p><p>14:00 – 16:00 Focus - Investing in New Knowledge</p><p>Chairperson – Dr. Christian Hoste, Deputy Director, AGREENIUM, The French Consortium for Research and Education in Agriculture, Food, Animal Health and the Environment, France</p><p>14:00 – 14:15 Overview of CTA’s SP 2011-2015 – Mr. Michael Hailu, Director, CTA, The Netherlands </p><p>14:15 – 14:30 Discussion </p><p>14:30 – 14:50 Strengthening ACP-EU Cooperation in Science and Research for Sustainable Development – Dr. John Kakule, Officer in charge of Science &amp; Technology, ACP Secretariat, Brussels </p><p>14:50 – 15:10 Strengthening Tertiary Education Systems for Agriculture and Science – Professor Adipala Ekwamu, RUFORUM Secretariat, Uganda</p><p>15:10 – 15:30 Strengthening Internal Science &amp; Technology Capacity in the Caribbean through Linkages, Exchange and Upgrading: Lessons from the EU-ACP Caribbean Welcome Project – Donald Miller, Research Officer, National Commission on Science and Technology, Jamaica</p><p>15:30 – 16:00 Discussion – Priorities, Policy Options and Strategies for Investing in New Knowledge and Strengthening S&amp;T Cooperation</p><p>16:00 – 16:30 Coffee Break</p><p>16:30 – 18:30 Focus: Strategic Priorities of the CTA S&amp;T Programme &amp; The Advisory Committee </p><p>Chairperson – Professor Hamidou Boly, President of Polytechnic University of Bobo Dioulasso, Burkina Faso </p><p>16:30 – 16:45 Taking Stock &amp; Learning Lessons from the CTA S&amp;T Strategies Programme: Key Messages from the Evaluation of the CTA SP 2007 - 2010 – Judith Ann Francis, CTA, The Netherlands</p><p>16:45 – 17:00 Discussion</p><p>17:00 – 18:00 Partners’ Platform – Experience Sharing &amp; Building Synergy through partnerships</p><p><i>ANAFE, AGRA, AGREENIUM, CARDI, CCST, CORAF-WECARD, CTA, FARA, ISHS, NEPAD Agency, RUFORUM, UWI, USP, WUR</i> (short 5 minute presentations on main achievements for 2011 &amp; proposals for 2012)</p><p>18:00 – 18:30 Discussion</p><p><b>Day 2 - October 10</b></p><p>8:30 – 13:00 Focus - Reducing Food Waste: Investing in Postharvest Knowledge Systems </p><p>Chairperson – Professor Agnes M’wangombe, Principal, College of Agriculture, University of Nairobi, Kenya</p><p>8:30 – 8:45 Key Messages from Day 1: Investing in New Knowledge - Wendy Sealy, Knowledge Management Consultant, Trinidad &amp; Tobago</p><p>8:45 – 9:15 Keynote Address – Postharvest Technology - Maintaining Quality and Reducing Losses and Wastage along the Supply Chain – Professor Linus Opara, Research Professor, Faculty of AgriSciences, Stellenbosch University, South Africa</p><p>9:15 – 9:35 Postharvest Handling of Fresh Produce in the Caribbean: Is UWI making a Difference? - Dr. Majeed Mohammed, Lecturer, UWI, St. Augustine Campus, Trinidad &amp; Tobago</p><p>9:35 – 9:55 The Post Harvest Program of the New Partnership for Africa’s Development Corporation Agency – Dr. Marcel Nwalozie, Director, NEPAD Agency, West Africa Mission, Senegal</p><p>9:55 – 10:15 The Trails of Food Waste – making a difference through research – Dr. Hilke Bos-Brouwers Project leader Sustainability, Food &amp; Biobased Research, Wageningen University &amp; research centre (WUR), The Netherlands</p><p>10:15 – 10:30 Discussion</p><p>10:30 – 11:00 Coffee Break</p><p>Chairperson – Dr Norah Omot, Director, Enabling Environment, National Agricultural Research Institute (NARI), Papua New Guinea </p><p>11:00 – 11:30 Value Addition – Processing as an Option: Lessons from Scientific Research Council, Jamaica – Dr. Chadwick Anderson, Executive Director, Scientific Research Council, Jamaica</p><p>11:30 – 12:00 Extending Food Shelf Life – New Technologies proposed by CIRAD - Dr. Didier Montet, Food Safety Team Manager, CIRAD-Persyst, CIRAD, France</p><p>12:00 – 12:30 Edible Vegetable Oilseed Crop Industry in Uganda: Lessons from the Uganda Oilseed Producers and Processors Association – Ray Agong, President, Uganda Oilseeds Association, Uganda</p><p>12:30 – 13:00 Discussion – Reducing Food Waste: Investing in Postharvest knowledge Systems</p><p>13:00 – 14:30 Lunch </p><p>14:30 – 16:00 Focus – Spreading Best Practice</p><p>Chairperson<i> </i>Prof. Ameenah Gurib-Fakim, Director &amp; Chair ICSU-ROA Council, CEPHYR Ltd, Mauritius</p><p>14:30 – 15:00 Sustainable Harvest from the Seas: Lessons from Local Fisheries in ACP Countries – Professor Stella Williams, Gender Specialist, and Organizational Facilitation, Obafemi Awolowo University, Nigeria.</p><p>15:00 – 15:30 Role of Policy Dialogue, Foresight and Linking Universities to Agribusiness for attracting increased National Funding: Lessons from the Forum for Agricultural Research in Africa - Ralph von Kaufmann, Technical Coordinator, Universities, Business and Research in Agricultural INnovation (UniBRAIN), FARA, Ghana</p><p>15:30 – 16:00 Discussion</p><p>16:00 – 16:30 Coffee Break</p><p>16:00 – 17:00 Working Group Session 1 – Investing in New Knowledge and Reducing Food Waste: Safeguarding the ACP Agri-food System</p><p>17:00 – 17:30 Presentation of Working Group Reports</p><p>17:30 – 18:00 Key Messages for the Alliance - Wendy Sealy, Knowledge Management Consultant, Trinidad &amp; Tobago</p><p><b>Day 3 - October 11 (Field Trip)</b></p><p>Focus: Postharvest Handling, Processing and Marketing </p><p>(i) Visit to Dominica Export Import Agency (DEXIA)</p><p>(ii) Visit to two outstanding Farmers in the Warner area; an open field CFC-EU R&amp;T project and a protected agriculture system facility</p><p>(iii) Farine (cassava) Processing Facility in Dipax</p><p>(iv) Lunch at Emerald Pool Tourist Facility</p><p><b>Day 4 - October 12 </b></p><p>8:30 - Depart Hotel for National Stadium</p><p>9:00 – 17:30 - Alliance Meeting &amp; Trade Show</p><p>Day 5 - October 13 </p><p>8:30 - 12:30 Focus: Future S&amp;T Priorities for Increasing Investments &amp; Improving the Evidence Base in the ACP region and Role &amp; Modus Operandi of the Advisory Committee on S&amp;T</p><p>Chairperson – Judith Ann Francis, CTA, The Netherlands</p><p>8:30 - 9:30 Plenary Discussion - Key Messages from Field Trip and Alliance Meeting – Wendy Sealy, Knowledge Management Consultant, Trinidad &amp; Tobago</p><p>9:30 – 11:00 Working Group Session 2 – Future S&amp;T Priorities &amp; AC Role and Modus Operandi: Towards a three year work programme</p><p>11:00 - 11:30 Coffee Break</p><p>11:30 – 12:30 Plenary</p><p>Presentation of Group Reports</p><p>Presentation of Draft Communiqué </p><p>Closing Remarks – AC Member and CTA Representatives</p><p>12:30 – 14:00 Lunch</p>
		


